  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Early identification, protection and support actions for newly displaced and conflict affected girls and boys Ninewa governorate</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This proposed action is part of an integrated and life-saving Child Protection (CP), Education, water, sanitation and hygiene (WASH) and Shelter (non-food items NFI) intervention. In order to address multiple needs of newly internally displaced persons (IDPs) fleeing in Ninewa governorate, Save the Children (SC) has decided to adopt a holistic approach aiming at fulfilling the existing gaps in four key humanitarian sectors. This project presents activities that are a continuation and expansion of a current CP IHPF project, linking closely with other SC projects responding to CP needs around Mosul. The project envisages enabling efficient operationalization of life-saving and time-critical activities to the most highly vulnerable girls and boys, focusing on acutely at risk children. Key response project modalities are child protection teams (4), protection desks (4), structured PSS support using different avance tools developed by SC including HART , and inclusion of resilience program  for children and youth   (5) and establishment and support of community based CP mechanisms. At the same time, the project aims to support existing activities in unaccompanied and separated children (UASC) support, including a transitional shelter, because of the close link with the case management and community support structures. 
In line with the identified Protection Cluster priorities the response section is targeting Ninewa governorate, CP teams will be deployed with capacity to rapidly identify critical CP needs and respond by means of direct support actions as well as linking up with established standard referral pathways in the target areas. Direct actions in first phase of displacement involve rapid identification and referral of emergency cases with emergency family care arrangements prioritized with pre-identification of families, support for transitional care tents for UASC (with minimum standards for interim care arrangement agreed upon with the CP SC), collection of key information on critical CP risk patterns which will inform advocacy efforts with key stakeholders, and dissemination of community-based messages on child safety, prevention of family separation and psychosocial support.</narrative>
  </description>
